          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> be a non-empty, connected, smooth scheme, with generic point <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\eta ]]></fr:tex>, and let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  X\to  S]]></fr:tex> be an abelian scheme over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>.
    The centre <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Z]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H=\operatorname {End}(\mathrm {R}_1f_*\mathbb {Z})]]></fr:tex> is then of degree <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(0,0)]]></fr:tex> (<fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.2.8" href="hodge-theory-ii-4.2.8.xml" taxon="Corollary" number="4.2.8" />), and thus contained in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {End}_S(X)\simeq \operatorname {End}_{k(\eta )}(X_\eta )]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>A polarisation of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> defines an involution <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[*]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex>.
    The restriction of this to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {End}_S(X)]]></fr:tex> is positive, so that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Z]]></fr:tex> is the product of completely real fields or quadratic imaginary extensions of completely real fields.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Denote by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C]]></fr:tex> the actions of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i\in  S(\mathbb {R})]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H_\mathbb {R}=H\otimes \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> and on the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(\mathrm {R}_1f_*\mathbb {R})_s]]></fr:tex> for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s\in  S]]></fr:tex>.
    On <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H_\mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C^2=1]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C]]></fr:tex> commutes with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[*]]></fr:tex>;
    on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(\mathrm {R}_1f_*\mathbb {R})_s]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C^2=-1]]></fr:tex>.
    If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\psi ]]></fr:tex> is the alternating form on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R}_1f_*\mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex> with integer values induced by the polarisation of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>, then
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       \psi (hx,Cy)       = \psi (x,h^*Cy)       = \psi (x,C\cdot  C(h^*)\cdot  y).     ]]></fr:tex>
    We thus deduce that

